</ul>
<img src=https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRQE5gVtunAft0wRq0TqLUOb2mnnnATPjipsQ&salt="Online Image" width="300">
<H1 Style="color: blue;">WATER ENTRIES </h1>
<ul>
<li>There are several ways to enter the water for a rescue. The
type of entry used depends on—</li>
<li> The depth of the water.</li>
<li>The lifeguard station—whether it is elevated or at
ground level.</li>
<li> Obstacles in the water, such as people, lane lines and
safety lines.</li>
<li> The location and condition of the victim.</li>
</ul>
<hr>COMPACT JUMP</hr>
<p>This entry is complete feet-first allowing for safer entry into
deep water. Primarily used in emergencies.</p>

</p> STRIDE ENTRY SAFETY STEPS</P>
<P> When entering water of known depth and conditions, from
standing position extend 1 leg some distance, slightly bend
the knees, lean forward and extend arms sideways.</P>
</P> THE BELLY FLOP STRIDE ENTRY</P>
<P>This type of entry is painful to the body but is considered as
one of the effectives entries that rescuers can use even in
the direst situations.</P>
<H1 Style="color: RED;">NOTE! </h1>
<P>The goal is to not lose sight or focus on the victim. So, a
water entry that does not have to dip your head underwater
is best to execute.</P>

Best water entries to execute
<ul>
<li>STRIDE</li>
<li>BELLY FLOP STRIDE ENTRY</li>

<hr>SAFETY EQUIPMENT RESCUE TUBE</hr>
<img src=https://eljansports.com/cdn/shop/products/EljanSports_NOA-Rescue-Tube-01_800x.jpg?v=1606765030 alt="Online Image" width="250">
<P>The rescue tube is a 45- to 54-inch vinyl, foam-
filled tube with an attached tow line and
shoulder strap. When performing patron
surveillance, a lifeguard should always keep a
rescue tube ready to use.</P>
<ul>
<li> Keep the strap of the rescue tube over the
shoulder and neck.</li>
<li>Hold the rescue tube across the thighs
when sitting in a lifeguard chair or across
the stomach when standing.</li>
<li>Hold the excess line to keep it from getting
caught in the chair or other equipment
when starting the rescue.</li>
</ul>
